In JIRA v1000.670.2 /  JIRA Agile v1000.269.0 there is no possibility to show parent/r task status in the swimmlane as it was possible by default in previous versions.  

See: https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSW-5397

*Pre-conditions:*
 - login with credentials of client user;
 - user2 in JIRA already exist;
 - verify and confirm that user can see only one specific project and tasks from it.

*STR 1:*
 - open specific project;
 - find users in the list of issues from Assignee or Reporter columns;
 - right click by user's name > Open the link in new tab;
 - look at the page with user's data.

{color:#333333}*Actual results:*{color}
 User's Full name and email are displayed on the page

*Expected results*:
 User's Full name and email are not displayed on the page

*STR 2:*
 - open Issue navigator of project
 - click 'Create' button of Jira Header menu
 - enter 'a.' to 'Watchers' field
 - look at the list of users

{color:#333333}*Actual results:*{color}
 Users of all projects are contained in the list whose Names are started from 'A' letter

*Expected results:*
 Users of only specific project are contained in the list whose Names are started from 'A' letter

*STR 3:*
 - open Issue navigator of project;
 - click 'Share' button above the table with issues;
 - enter 'a.' to 'User name or email' field;
 - look at the list of users.

{color:#333333}*Actual results:*{color}
 Users of all projects are contained in the list whose Names are started from 'A' letter

{color:#333333}*Expected results:*{color}
 Users of only specific project are contained in the list whose Names are started from 'A' letter

*STR 4:*
 - open user Profile
 - add '?name=user2' to the end of URL
 - click 'Enter'
 - look at the opened page

*{color:#333333}Actual results:{color}*
 Full name and email of user2 are displayed on the page

{color:#333333}*Expected results:*{color}
 Full name and email of user2 are not displayed on the page

Please, suggest, what we can do in this cases, thank you in advance!

JIRA Software's Version Report provides inconsistent data regarding the estimate displayed. Please see Anton's very detailed answer regarding this:

 

First of all, all calculation happens on client side, in JavaScript.
Here is a function:

{noformat}
ReleaseDatePredictor.getCompletedEstimatePerDay = function (completedEstimateDataPoints, startTime, endTime, seriesDataPoints) \{
 var completedData = [];
 var currentEstimateCompleted = 0;
 var currentIndex = 0;
 var issuesCounted = [];
 var workingDays = 0;

function addToIssuesCounted(issue) \{
 // keep track of burned down issues
 var changeEvent = ChangeEvent.getChangeEvent(issue);
 if (changeEvent == ChangeEvent.burndown || changeEvent == ChangeEvent.completeScopeAdded) \{
 issuesCounted.push(issue.key);
 }
 }

function removeEstimateAlreadyCounted(currentComplete, issue) \{
 // if we already counted this issue in the burndown
 if (_.contains(issuesCounted, issue.key)) \{
 // if it's now being re-added to scope, don't count it again
 var changeEvent = ChangeEvent.getChangeEvent(issue);
 if (changeEvent === ChangeEvent.completeScopeAdded || changeEvent === ChangeEvent.scopeAdded) \{
 return currentComplete - issue.completedEstimate;
 }
 }

return currentComplete;
 }

// for each day since the start of the chart, check for estimate completed
 for (var i = startTime; i <= endTime; i += ChartUtils.oneDayInMillis) \{
 // ignore non-working days
 if (!BurndownRate.isDateInNonWorkingBlock(i)) \{
 workingDays++;
 }

var completedToday = 0;
 var issuesChanged;
 // check the next data point in the series
 for (var j = currentIndex; j < completedEstimateDataPoints.length; j++) \{
 var dateOfChange = completedEstimateDataPoints[j][0];

// if this occurred in the last day, add it
 if (dateOfChange <= i) \{
 // if we didn't already pass the start time, don't add the points
 if (dateOfChange > startTime) \{
 var estimate = completedEstimateDataPoints[j][1];

// track the burned down issues we count and reduce estimate for those we've already counted e.g. re-added scope
 issuesChanged = (seriesDataPoints[j]) ? seriesDataPoints[j].issues : [];
 if (issuesChanged) \{
 estimate = _.reduce(issuesChanged, removeEstimateAlreadyCounted, estimate);
 _.each(issuesChanged, addToIssuesCounted);
 }

if (estimate > currentEstimateCompleted) \{
 // Add the difference between the last change and the current value
 completedToday += (estimate - currentEstimateCompleted);
 }
 // Reset the current value to compare for next time
 currentEstimateCompleted = completedEstimateDataPoints[j][1];
 } else \{
 // still want to add to the issues we've counted so we don't count it again
 issuesChanged = (seriesDataPoints[j]) ? seriesDataPoints[j].issues : [];
 if (issuesChanged) \{
 _.each(issuesChanged, addToIssuesCounted);
 }
 // also need to reset the current estimate completed
 currentEstimateCompleted = completedEstimateDataPoints[j][1];
 }
 } else \{
 // Passed today, reset index for next loop
 currentEstimateCompleted = completedEstimateDataPoints[j][1];
 currentIndex = j;
 break;
 }
 }

completedData.push(
 \{
 time: i,
 estimate: completedToday
 }
 );

}
 return \{
 completedData: completedData,
 workingDays: workingDays
 };
 };
{noformat}

This function is responsible for evaluation of how much of estimate is done per period from the start day of the version, up to now. In order to do so, it receives list of completed estimates with timestamps when they was completed, start time, end time and list of issues completed in specified period.

For some reason, "end time" is in future. 24 hours in future. I tried to changed it to simple "now" value, but then everything falls apart.
Also for some reason for one completed estimate this method receives list of 3 estimates.
First estimate equals zero. Second estimate is the real estimate and the third one is fake estimate, just a copy of second estimate (please, somebody, shoot me).

Anyhow, the algorithm works in that way that it adds completed estimate only for previous days, not for "today". But it counts working days for every day it iterates.

Looking at at the picture:
[^image_2016-12-01_18-21-14.png]
JIRA Agile starts with "start" date, which is midnight of current day, today is working day, so it increases number of working days. Working Days = 1. 
Next, it takes first completed estimate from the list, checks if it happened "last day", it this case it is didn't, so it skips it (but that doesn't matter because first completed estimate is zero anyway).
Now, JIRA Agile goes further through time (not through space, though >_<), by adding 24 hours to "start" value. Next, JIRA increases number of working days by 1. So there is 2 working days already.
After that, JIRA takes a completed estimate from list of completed estimates, and thinks that it happened "yesterday", so it adds amount of completed estimate to "Total Amount Of Completed Estimate". It is still zero though. But we have 3 completed estimates in the list. So JIRA just takes next completed estimate and adds it to Total Completed Estimate. This time it was 1d (8 hours), so Total Completed Estimate = 1 day. Now it takes 3d and last completed estimate. It compares it with completed issues in "seriesDataPoints" list and understands that we've already added this estimate, because it the same estimate as estimate 2 in this list (really, somebody, shoot me already), so it skips it.
Ok, next cycle, next day, JIRA adds 24 more hours to "start" value and understands that it bigger than "end" value, so it considers that everything is done.

So, we have that JIRA thinks that there are *2* working days and there is only *1* day of completed estimate. This leads to predicted velocity of *4* hours a day instead of *8* hours a day and makes predicted completion day 2 times further in future that it is in reality.

The  futureSprint() function is not added yet in the documentation.
